8.1 The components of a graph

This data visualization shows us pretty much all the information in the data table.

The first step in learning ggplot2: to be able to break a graph apart into components Main three components: Data Geometry: scatterplot, barplot, histogram, smooth densities, qqplot, boxplot, etc. Aesthetic mapping: uses visual cues to represent the information. x-axis, y-axis. color.

also note that * Points are labeled with the state abbreviations * x-axis, y-axis: range of the data, both log scale * labels, title, legend, style of the economist magazine

library(dslabs)
data(murders)

8.3 Geometries

We create graphs by adding layers. Layers : define geometries, compute summary statistics, define scales, change styles. we use ‘+’ to add layers

DATA %>% ggplot() + LAYER 1 + LAYER 2 + … + LAYER N

the first added layer defines the geometry function used to create scatterplot : ‘geom_point’

Geometry function names follow the pattern: geom_X (X = name of the geometry)

to find out what mappings are expected ; we read Aesthetics section of the help file:

Aesthetics

geom_point understands the following aesthetics (required aesthetics are in bold):

x

y

alpha

colour

at least two arguments required : x and y

8.4 Aesthetic mappings

describe how data connect with graph; distance along axis, size or color

function ‘aes’ connects data with what we see on the graph, often used as the argument of a geometry fuction

# total murders versus population in millions, scatterplot

murders %>% ggplot() + 
  geom_point(aes(x = population/10^6, y = total))

We can drop ‘x=’ and ‘y=’ if we wanted to we can also add a layer to the p object that was defined above

p + geom_point(aes(population/10^6, total))

scale and labels are defined by default ‘aes’ also uses variable names from the object component

8.5 Layers

A second layer in the plot involves adding a label function ‘geom_label’, ‘geom_text’: add text to the plot with and without a rectangle behind the text

each pointhas a label: we need aesthetic mapping to make the connectino between points and labels

we supply the mapping between point and label through the ‘label’ argument of ‘aes’.

p + geom_point(aes(population/10^6, total)) +
  geom_text(aes(population/10^6, total, label = abb))

we added a second layer!

this call is fine

p_test <- p + geom_text(aes(population/10^6, total, label = abb))

whereas this call

p_test <- p + geom_text(aes(population/10^6, total), label = abb)
Error in layer(data = data, mapping = mapping, stat = stat, geom = GeomText,  : 
  object 'abb' not found

gives error since ‘abb’ not found

8.5.1 Tinkering with arguments

‘size’ is an aesthetic and we can change

p + geom_point(aes(population/10^6, total), size = 3) +
  geom_text(aes(population/10^6, total, label = abb))

‘size’ is not a mapping, whereas mapping need to be inside aes()

affect points -> don’t need to be included inside ‘aes’

points are larger, so hard to see the labels argument ‘nudge_x’: moves the text slightly to the right or to the left

p + geom_point(aes(population/10^6, total), size = 3) +
  geom_text(aes(population/10^6, total, label = abb), nudge_x = 1)

8.6 Global versus local aesthetic mappings

we can use a global aesthetic mapping to avoid defining the mapping twice can do this when defining blank state ‘ggplot’ object

args(ggplot)
function (data = NULL, mapping = aes(), ..., environment = parent.frame()) 
NULL

if we define a mapping in ‘ggplot’, all the geometires that are added as layers will default

p <- murders %>% ggplot(aes(population/10^6, total, label = abb))

the code becomes simple

p + geom_point(size = 3) + 
  geom_text(nudge_x = 1.5)

we keep ‘size’ and ‘nudge_x’ arguments in ‘geom_point’ and ‘geom_text’ respectively. If we put those arguments in ‘aes’ then they would apply to both points and labels

‘geom_point’ function does not need a ‘label’ argument and ignores the aesthetic

we can override global mapping by defining a new mapping within each layer : ‘local’ definitions

p + geom_point(size = 3) +  
  geom_text(aes(x = 10, y = 800, label = "Hello there!"))

8.7 Scales

Our desired scales are in log-scale, which is not the default ‘scale_x_continuous’ function lets us control the behavior of scales

p + geom_point(size = 3) +  
  geom_text(nudge_x = 0.05) + 
  scale_x_continuous(trans = "log10") +
  scale_y_continuous(trans = "log10")

nudge must be made smaller cuz we are i the log-scale now

ggplot2 provides ‘scale_x_log10’ and ‘scale_y_log10’

p + geom_point(size = 3) +  
  geom_text(nudge_x = 0.05) + 
  scale_x_log10() +
  scale_y_log10()

8.8 Labels and Titles

p + geom_point(size = 3) +  
  geom_text(nudge_x = 0.05) + 
  scale_x_log10() +
  scale_y_log10() +
  xlab("Populations in millions (log scale)") + 
  ylab("Total number of murders (log scale)") +
  ggtitle("US Gun Murders in 2010")

xlab, ylab, ggtitle -> for titles

8.9 Categories as colors

we can change color of points using ‘col’ argument in the ‘geom_point’ function.

p <-  murders %>% ggplot(aes(population/10^6, total, label = abb)) +   
  geom_text(nudge_x = 0.05) + 
  scale_x_log10() +
  scale_y_log10() +
  xlab("Populations in millions (log scale)") + 
  ylab("Total number of murders (log scale)") +
  ggtitle("US Gun Murders in 2010")
p + geom_point(size=3, color="blue")

we want to assign color depending on the geographical region

if we assign a categorical variable to color, it automatically assigns a different color to each category, and adds a legend

this is an aesthetic mapping, and use ‘aes’

p + geom_point(aes(col=region), size = 3)

‘x’ and ‘y’ mappings are from those already defined i ‘p’ we also move ‘aes’ to the first argument; where mappings are expected in this function call

ggplo2 automatically adds a legend that maps color to region to avoid this, we use arguent show.legend = FALSE’

8.10 Annotation, Shapes, and adjustments

we often want to add shapes or annotation to figures that are not derived directly from the aesthetic mapping

we want to add a line ; average murder rate for the entire country

we define per million rate to be r, this line is defined by the formula: y=rx, with ‘y’ = total murders, ‘x’ = population in millions

in the log scale, log(y) = log(r) + log(x)

In our plot it’s a line with slope 1 and intercept log(r)

r <- murders %>% 
  summarize(rate = sum(total) /  sum(population) * 10^6) %>% 
  pull(rate)

to add a line, we use the ‘geom_abline’ ggplot2 uses ‘ab’ in the name to remind us we are supplying the intercept (a) and slope (b)

default: slope 1, intercept 0

p + geom_point(aes(col=region), size = 3) + 
  geom_abline(intercept = log10(r))

here ‘geom_abline’ does not use any information from the data object

we can change the line type and color of the lines using arguments. also we draw it first ; it doesn’t go over our points

p <- p + geom_abline(intercept = log10(r), lty = 2, color = "darkgrey") +
  geom_point(aes(col=region), size = 3)

we have redefined p and used this new p below and in the next section

we frequently need to make minor tweaks to the default we can make changes to the legend via the function ‘scale_color_discrete’

p <- p + scale_color_discrete(name = "Region")
p

8.12 Putting it all together

install.packages("ggrepel")
Error in install.packages : Updating loaded packages
library(ggthemes)
library(ggrepel)

r <- murders %>% 
  summarize(rate = sum(total) /  sum(population) * 10^6) %>%
  pull(rate)

murders %>% ggplot(aes(population/10^6, total, label = abb)) +   
  geom_abline(intercept = log10(r), lty = 2, color = "darkgrey") +
  geom_point(aes(col=region), size = 3) +
  geom_text_repel() + 
  scale_x_log10() +
  scale_y_log10() +
  xlab("Populations in millions (log scale)") + 
  ylab("Total number of murders (log scale)") +
  ggtitle("US Gun Murders in 2010") + 
  scale_color_discrete(name = "Region") +
  theme_economist()

8.13 Quick plots with ‘qplot’

there are instances in which all we want is to make a quick plot if we want to keep consistent with ggplot style(not using hist, plot and boxplot) we can use the functino ‘qplot’

# values in two vectors
data(murders)
x <- log10(murders$population)
y <- murders$total

we want to make scatterplot with ggplot

data.frame(x = x, y = y) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x, y)) +
  geom_point()

seems like too much code! ‘qplot’ function allows us to generate a plot quickly

qplot(x, y)

8.1 Grids of plots

there are reasons to graph plots next to each other ; ‘gridextra’ package

install.packages("gridExtra")
Error in install.packages : Updating loaded packages
library(gridExtra)
p1 <- murders %>%
  mutate(rate = total/population*10^5) %>%
  filter(population < 2*10^6) %>%
  ggplot(aes(population/10^6, rate, label = abb)) +
  geom_text() +
  ggtitle("Small States")

p2 <- murders %>%
  mutate(rate = total/population*10^5) %>%
  filter(population > 10*10^6) %>%
  ggplot(aes(population/10^6, rate, label = abb)) +
  geom_text() +
  ggtitle("Large States")

grid.arrange(p1, p2, ncol = 2)
